At 01:55 PM 1/15/05, cree fetterman wrote:

>I am sorry but I am pretty sure you would have to balance a piston closer
to the "X" amount of grams that a dime weighs. If you

 

IIRC, a quarter weighs five grams (been a long time since I read Muir).
Factory spec for

balancing pistons is "within 10 grams". Since a dime weighs less than a
quarter and

since I wasn't building a race motor, getting them to weigh "the same"
within the

margin of error involved with the average weight of a dime was close enough.
I built

that engine with 95% used parts (new rings, exhaust valves & valve springs)
and got

60k miles out of it before an oil pump failure killed it .. far more than I
was expecting.

 

I was relating my experience to others on the list with the idea that
someone might

appreciate the creative solution I came up with given the tools, equipment
and finances

available at the time, nothing more.

 


